x4freetext: NO DETAILS GIVEN
.DATA TAKEN FROM MAIN REF.
S.W.
SPIN VALUES TAKEN FROM
RIEHS AND THOMAS (1974) PROC 2ND INT SYMP ON NEUTRON
CAPTURE GAMMA-RAY SPECTROSCOPY AND RELATED TOPICS,
PETTEN, THE NETHERLANDS, P 300.
NEUTRON WIDTHS TAKEN
FROM BNL-325, 3RD EDITION.
.PEAK BEAM CURRENT OF 1 AMP, PULSE WIDTH 80 NS AND
REPETITION RATE 150 PPS.
. 99.99% PURE CS2CO3 IN A 0.1 MM THICK AL CAN, 6 CM IN
DIAMETER AND THICKNESS 0.00587 ATOMS/BARN FOR 133-CS.
THE SAMPLE WAS POSITIONED 51.94 M FROM THE NEUTRON
PRODUCING TARGET.
3500 L LIQUID SCINTILLATOR TANK TO DETECT
PROMPT GAMMAS.
11.1 CM DIAM AND 0.635 CM THICK LI-6 GLASS
SCINTILLATOR FOR TRANSMITTED N-FLUX, PLACED 4 M DOWN-
STREAM FROM SAMPLE POSITION.
ANOTHER LI-6 GLASS DETECTOR AT THE 47 M STATION
MEASURED INCIDENT N-FLUX.
52 M FLIGHT PATH
.THE RATIO OF THE EFFICIENCIES OF THE CAPTURE AND THE
NEUTRON FLUX DETECTORS WAS DETERMINED BY A SATURATED
RESONANCE METHOD, USING THE RESONANCE AT 47.8 EV AND
AN ITERATIVE CALCULATION WITH THE MONTE CARLO CODE
TACASI AND INITIAL RESONANCE PARAMETERS FROM BNL-325,
3RD EDITION. FINAL PARAMETERS FOR THIS RESONANCE WERE
DETERMINED FROM THE INTERSECTION OF THE TWO CURVES
FOR CAPTURE AND TRANSMISSION:
N-WIDTH = 21.6 MILLI-EV
G-WIDTH = 106.4 MILLI-EV
CAPTURE AREAS FOR EACH RESONANCE WERE THEN
CALCULATED BY THE MONTE CARLO CODE TACASI USING THE
NORMALISED CAPTURE YIELDS AND THE NEUTON WIDTHS FROM
BNL-325, 3RD EDITION.
.CAPTURE YIELD CORRECTED FOR DEAD TIME LOSSES AND
BACKGROUND. THE BACKGROND FOR THE TRANSMITTED N-FLUX
DETERMINED FROM COUNTS AT THE BLACK RESONANCES AT
47.8 EV OF 133-CS AND 2.8 KEV 23-NA (FOR WHICH PURPOSE
AN 8 MM THICK METALLIC NA SAMPLE WAS KEPT IN THE
NEUTRON BEAM THROUGHOUT THE EXPERIMENT). THE BACK-
GROUND OF THE CAPTURE SPECTRUM WAS FROM OFF-RESONANCE
REGION COUNTS OF 133-CS AND 23-NA (2.8 KEV)
DOUBLET
TRIPLET
.DATA TAKEN FROM TABLE 1 OF MAIN REF.
S.W.
